ncie","France":"Francie"},"da":{"1012–1072":"1012–1072","1013–1086":"1013–1086","1020–Male":"1020–Afdød","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–1124":"1030–1124","1030–Male":"1030–Afdød","1019–1080":"1019–1080","1043–Female":"1043–Afdød","0978–1038":"0978–1038","1080":"1080","Cir 1038":"1038","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1019":"1019","1038":"1038","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1013":"1013","1012":"1012","about 1038":"1038","0978":"0978","Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, Frankrig","Craon, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Craon, Anjou, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"1012–1072":"1012–1072","1013–1086":"1013–1086","1020–Male":"1020–Overleden","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–1124":"1030–1124","1030–Male":"1030–Overleden","1019–1080":"1019–1080","1043–Female":"1043–Overleden","0978–1038":"0978–1038","1080":"1080","Cir 1038":"1038","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1019":"1019","1038":"1038","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1013":"1013","1012":"1012","about 1038":"1038","0978":"0978","Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, Frankrijk","Craon, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Craon, Anjou, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"1012–1072":"1012–1072","1013–1086":"1013–1086","1020–Male":"1020–Deceased","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–1124":"1030–1124","1030–Male":"1030–Deceased","1019–1080":"1019–1080","1043–Female":"1043–Deceased","0978–1038":"0978–1038","1080":"1080","Cir 1038":"1038","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1019":"1019","1038":"1038","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1013":"1013","1012":"1012","about 1038":"1038","0978":"0978","Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France","Craon, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France":"Craon, Anjou, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Craon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Krahn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Krahn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Gerd, Gerhard, Hans, Hans-Peter, Horst, Irmgard, Mathias, Otto, Wilhelm, Willi.","German: nickname for a tall, slim long-legged person, from Middle Low German <i>krane</i> ‘crane’. Compare   Kranich  ."]}]},{"name":"Guérin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Marcel, Normand, Andre, Dominique, Aime, Alain, Arsene, Benoit, Francois, Gilles.","French (<b>Guérin</b>) and Irish (of French Huguenot origin): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Warino</i>, Latinized as <i>Guarinus</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France, partly as a result of the popularity of the Carolingian lay <i>Guérin de Montglave</i>. This was the name of several Huguenot families who came to England as refugees at different times in the 16th and 17th centuries. The surname became established as a surname in Ireland (County Limerick) as early as the 16th century. Compare   Garin  ,   Garing  ,   Gearing  ,   Geren  ,   Geron  ,   Gerren  ,   Geurin  ,   Guerrant  , and   Ward  .","Italian (Friuli Venezia Giulia): variant of   Guerino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Guerrant","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","In some cases possibly also French (Seine-Maritime): variant of <b>Guerrand</b>, a nickname for a belligerent person or alternatively for a valiant soldier, derived from <i>guerrer</i> ‘to fight’. The surname <i>Guerrant</i> is very rare in France.","History: Daniel Guérin/Guerrant from Saint-Nazaire-sur-Charente in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie L'Orange in Saint-Nazaire in 1697, died in Goochland, VA, in 1721. His name is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Gearing","meanings":["English (Sussex and London): perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>gering</i>, apparently with the sense ‘lecher; glutton’.","English (of French Huguenot origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","Americanized form of German   Gehring   or of some other similar (like-sounding) German surname (compare e.g.   Gahring   and   Garing  )."]},{"name":"Geren","meanings":["Shortened form of the biblical name <i>Keren-happuch</i>, borne by the third of Job's daughters (Job 42:14). The name meant ‘horn of eye-paint’ in Hebrew."]},{"name":"Garin","meanings":["Of Celtic origin, but uncertain ultimate derivation; it first appears in French sources as <i>Gauvain</i>. The name is borne in the Arthurian romances by one of the knights of the Round Table (more familiar in English versions as Sir  <b>Gawain</b> ). It was still in use in the north of England as late as the early 18th century and never died out in Scotland, whence it was reintroduced to England from the early 20th century. It is now very widely used in England, Wales, and elsewhere in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Gerren","meanings":["Altered form of   Darren ."]},{"name":"Geurin","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"\"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bâtard\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Vilaire, Alcee, Antoine, Franck, Ghislaine, Marcel.","French: from Old French <i>baiart</i> ‘bay-colored’, a nickname for someone with reddish-brown hair. Compare 2 below.","English (of Norman origin): from <i>Bayard</i>, the name of the bright bay magic horse given by Charlemagne to Renaud in a 12th-century chanson de geste, derived from Old French <i>baiart</i> (as in 1 above). It was subsequently used as a mock-heroic name for any horse, particularly for a blindly reckless or foolish one. Applied as a nickname it probably denoted someone with a proud, haughty, or reckless disposition, rather than someone with reddish brown hair."],"variants":[{"name":"Bayardo","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): probably an altered form of French   Bayard  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guérin \"le Bâtard\" de Craon was born in 1012, in Craon, Anjou, France as the son of Suhard de Craon seigneur de Craon. He married Anne de Crequy in 1038, in Mayenne, Pays de la Loire, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1072, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1012–1072":"1012–1072","1013–1086":"1013–1086","1020–Male":"1020–Surnud","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–1124":"1030–1124","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1019–1080":"1019–1080","1043–Female":"1043–Surnud","0978–1038":"0978–1038","1080":"1080","Cir 1038":"1038","1043":"1043","1020":"1020","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1019":"1019","1038":"1038","1124":"1124","1025":"1025","1013":"1013","1012":"1012"